title: For Sale:  Mauser Banner Police Luger, 2 digit date, Scarce
postcontent: This is a scarce two digit date '42' eagle L police luger. According to some research this was the last Police order in 1942 from Mauser consisting of 300 lugers in the serial # range 7901y-8300y. The serial # on this one is 8187y. Some were with sear safties, some wheren't. Some had serial numbered barrels, some didn't. This one has the hole in the frame for a sear safety but none was ever installed. According to research the factory making sear safties was destroyed by an allied bombing raid in 1941. I suppose that they installed what they could come up with. The barrel on this one is not numbered. It is all matching from my inspection. I have not stripped it down because I don't want to chance adding scratches, etc. The collector that I got it from said he had taken it apart once and the internal #s matched. A local gunsmith rated it 98%-98%+. Whatever number you assign it; it is a beauty and with 2 matching mags, marked 1&2, with eagle L on bases and fxo and P.08 on mag bodies with eagle/37. The frame is marked on left side P.08 and with the Eagle over N. Right side of frame with Eagle L. It has the walnut grips.

title: For Sale:  Marlin Slugmaster 512 with rifled barrel
postcontent: I have killed several deer with this gun but the reason I am getting rid of it is because I am going to try a muzzleloader. It is a heavy barrel and a bit of a heavy gun and since I am getting a bit older I think I better lighten my load some since I walk through the state forest for miles at a time when I hunt.  I shoot the Winchester partition gold slugs 2 3/4". They really pack a punch and cost around $15 per box at Dunhams but they are very accurate and very powerful.  I have an extra butt pad on the gun to absorb the shoulder impact and that really helps a lot.  My third daughter killed a nice big doe at 135 yards this year with this gun and doesn't want me to sell it but I think I better.  If you prefer a very sensitive trigger do not buy this gun as it has a bit of a stiff trigger and it is something you'd have to get used to I think.  I'm going to leave the scope on it till I sell it but I am going to take it off and put my 4x Simmons on it since my wife got this Cabela's scope for me for Christmas I better save it :). I also would like to keep my strap. Email me for more pictures or questions please. Thank you

There are many on the market and the one included is the Army issue one, which frankly is substandard at best.  Other than that, you are getting a great helmet that has a few scuffs, but is otherwise in superb condition.  Please do not confuse this with the much cheaper Kevlar Helmets of years before.

I am full time in Law Enforcement and I will only sell this to professionals.  Make me a serious offer.  Cheers!
